In [102]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Ensure 'Reviews' is numeric and handle non-numeric values
data['Reviews'] = pd.to_numeric(data['Reviews'], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with NaN values in 'Reviews'
data = data.dropna(subset=['Reviews'])

# Group by 'Category' and calculate mean of 'Reviews'
category_review = data.groupby('Category')['Reviews'].mean().reset_index()

# Rename columns for clarity
category_review.columns = ['category', 'review']

# Sort by 'review' in descending order
sorted_data = category_review.sort_values(by='review', ascending=False)

# Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
sns.barplot(x='category', y='review', data=sorted_data)
plt.xticks(rotation=80)
plt.xlabel("Category")
plt.ylabel("Average Reviews")
plt.title("Category and Average Reviews")
plt.show()

In [104]:
category_list = list(data['Category'].unique())
category_install = []
for i in category_list:
    x = data[data['Category'] == i]
    if(len(x)!=0):
        install = sum(x.Installs)/len(x)
        category_install.append(install)
    else:
        install = sum(x.Installs)
        category_install.append(install)
